description.narrative: By 2022, the country will have the capacity to implement a model for maternal and neonatal health services that is consistent with quality care standards including prevention of obstetric violence., which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Disaster Risk Reduction, Early Childhood Development, Hiv Prevention, Maternal And Newborn Health, Water. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, pregnant women, newborns and adolescents will access high-quality health services.

description.narrative: UNICEF strengthened the progressive ownership of the initiative “Mothers and Babies in Good Care” by the NHS. As a result, 19 hospitals improved their quality standards compliance. Nine of them reached 75% of these standards. 45% of all the children born in public hospitals were born in these 9 hospitals. UNICEF collaborated to improve the supply chain of ARVT and promoted the design of a short term plan to reduce the mother-to-child HIV transmission (MTCT). The implementation of the Zika project improved the health and education sectors, as well as the Social Protection program. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:04/02/2020
